bi: , akamubi, am bithear? am biteas?1, cha bhi sinn, bier, biarentzat, nach robh iad?, cha bithear, cha bitear, cha bitheas1, awumubi, esibi, nach bi thu?, (a) bhios tu, nach bitheadh sibh?, lelibi, bitik, nach eil sinn?, am bite(adh)? am bithist(e)?1, is sibh, bhitheadh e/i, bitheadh iad, bitzat, biri, tha mi, biek, nach robh sinn?, bissä, bina, an robh mi?, nach bi mi?, esingesibi, bithibh, bhithinn, biarengatik, lengimubi, bhitheadh sinnbhitheamaid, cha bhitheadh sibh, a bhith, Note: Some of these forms may be hypothetical. Not every possible mutated form of every word actually occurs., biiltä, cha bhi iad, okubi, cha bhi thu, biers, bidh e/i, chan eil iad, biille, birengana, biengandik, cha bu mhi, ababi, lomubi, cha sinn, am bitheadh tu?, am beilear? am beileas?1  a bheilear? a bheileas?1, am bitheadh e/i?, bins, mibi, am bu tu?, bistä, nach bithinn?, am b' iad?, engembi, kubi, bhiodh sibh, cha bu tu, ayiyimbi, birekin, biltä, (a) bhitheas e/i, bira, nach bitheadh e/i?, cha b' iad, bien, cha robh thu, enibabi, bietarantz, biekin, biineen, babi, elingelibi, birengatik, engimubi, bitaraino, bhiodh e/i, cha robh sinn, libi, bhitheadh tu, an robhar? an robhas?1, timbi, nach e/i?, bhathar, bhatar, bhathas1, biak, nach eilear? nach eileas?1, cha bu sibh, ongembi, nach tu?, nach b' iad?, cha sibh, bidh sinn, biissä, cha bhi mi, bhiodh sinnbhiomaid, nach bithear? nach bitear? nach bitheas?1, bubi, (a) bhios mi, is e/i, lembi, nach eil e/i?, chan eil thu, am bi e/i?, angemabi, nach bi e/i?, bhitheadh iad, asibabi, engemibi, biaz, am b' e/i?, biaren, cha bhithinn, nach robhar? nach robhas?1, lababi, bu sibh, biens, överall bi, bitheam, nach mi?, biengana, am mi?, zimbi, biittä, a bheil e/i?, is iad, biitä, bia, biillä, biarengana, bhiodh iad, ayimibi, bi, am biodh sibh?, biei, dorbi, bha mi, bitara, bitarako, biko, chan eil e/i, lemibi, an robh thu?, alilibi, asisibi, cha bhiodh iad, chan eil sibh, (a) bhitheas iad, bitheamaid, bienganaino, bitatik, a bheil sibh?, (a) bhios sibh, nach eil thu?, nach b' e/i?, bietako, bha thu, cha robh mi, chan eil sinn, bithidh sibh, elibi, mubi, biarengandik, okungekubi, cha bhitheadh e/i, biistä, biraino, nach bite(adh)? diviti: bȉo sam divio2, divljasmo, divili bi2, divio m / divila f / divilo n, bíli biste divili2, bȕdū divili2, divio bi2, bíli bi divili2, divio si2, bíli smo divili2, divljah, divili su2, bȉo je divio2, divi, divljaše, bíli ste divili2, divili bismo2, divili biste2, divili m / divile f / divila n, bȉo si divio2, divimo, Future I, divio je2, 1   Croatian spelling: others omit the infinitive suffix completely and bind the clitic.2   For masculine nouns; a feminine or neuter agent would use the feminine and neuter gender forms of the active past participle and auxiliary verb, respectively.3   Often replaced by the past perfect in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
4   Often replaced by the conditional I in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.

ropa: , ropist (þið), ropám, rōpar, rōpins, ropad, ropandist ** ** the mediopassive present participle is extremely rare and normally not used; it is never used attributively or predicatively, only for explicatory subclauses, þið ropuðuð, ropami, þið ropuðust, ropą, hann, hún, það ropist, hann, hún, það ropaði, ropuðu, ropaðu, hann, hún, það ropast, rōpaþu, -o, þið ropist, ropuðum, við ropumst, þið ropið, þú ropist, við ropuðumst, * Spoken form, usually not written; in writing, the unappended plural form (optionally followed by the full pronoun) is preferred., þēr, þú ropir, ropen, rōpaþis, -es, þeir, þær, þau ropast, ég ropa, rōpaþums, -oms, þeir, þær, þau ropi, ég ropist, ropaðan, ropaður, ropaðrar, ropes, að ropast, ropaðs, ropaðri, ropu, rōpaþi, -e, þeir, þær, þau ropuðust, rōpis, -es, við ropum, ropy, við ropuðum, rōpaþer, ropiði *, rōpi, -e, rope, īr, rōpums, -oms, ropaðra, ropades, ég ropast, ropast (þú), hann, hún, það ropi, ropě, ropastu, rōpaþin, ropas, ég ropaðist, ropisti *, ropats, ég ropi, þeir, þær, þau ropa, ropast, þú ropaðist, að ropa, rōpum, -om, rōpaþum, -om, ropou, ropách, 1 Archaic. 2 Dated. lacer: lacer, , avoir lacé, laceras, laçoient, laceient, laçoent, lacevent, laças, lacez, laça, laceroie, lacereie, laçât/la.sa/, lacissons, lacissiens, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., laçasses/la.sas/, lace, lacent, lacèrent/la.sɛʁ/, laciiens, laciens, laçais/la.sɛ/, laçons/la.sɔ̃/, lacerōs, laceront/la.sʁɔ̃/, laçâmes/la.sam/, lacerō, laceroiz, lacereiz, lacerez, lacissoiz, lacissez, lacissiez, laces, laceras/la.sʁa/, Use the gerund of avoir followed by the past participle, lacent/las/, lacerons, laceraient/la.sʁɛ/, laçassions/la.sa.sjɔ̃/, laciez/la.sje/, laçast, laz, laceront, laçaient/la.sɛ/, lacerā, lacions/la.sjɔ̃/, lacé/la.se/, laçant, lacerai/la.sʁe/, laçasse/la.sas/, laçoie, laceie, laçoe, laceve, laceriiens, laceriens, laçai/la.se/, lacerae, laceroient, lacereient, laçasse, laçastes, laçasses, laçoies, laceies, laçoes, laceves, laceriiez, laceriez, lacerais/la.sʁɛ/, lacerōrum, laçames, lazt, laçassent/la.sas/, lacerum, laça/la.sa/, laçoit, laceit, laçot, laceve, laceroit, lacereit, laceriez/la.sə.ʁje/, lacez/la.se/, laçassiez/la.sa.sje/, lacé, lacera/la.sʁa/, en laçant, lacerait/la.sʁɛ/, laces/las/, laçant/la.sɑ̃/, lacerez/la.sʁe/, laçai, lacerent, laçâtes/la.sat/, laceram, lacerons/la.sʁɔ̃/, lacerions/la.sə.ʁjɔ̃/, lacerīs, laças/la.sa/, lacerai, laçons, lace/las/, lacera, laçait/la.sɛ/, lacerārum, —, laciiez, laciez, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., laceroies, lacereies, laçassent, lacerās, lacerī

munda: , mundisti *, mundaðar, 1 In imperative: used only in the second-person singular. The plural form is used with other persons., þeir, þær, þau munduðu, muniži, ég mundi, mundaðir, þið mundist, mundiði *, munižim, ég mundaðist, munid, við mundum, munind, hann, hún, það mundist, munnugoi, ég mundast, þið mundið, munnuižin, við munduðum, munnuižiba, * Spoken form, usually not written; in writing, the unappended plural form (optionally followed by the full pronoun) is preferred., mundað, munnet, munižiba, muniba, þeir, þær, þau munda, munnem, að munda, munmat, mundaðrar, munne, mundaðs, hann, hún, það mundi, munnu, mungat, mungam, munnuižit, munda, munduð, ég mundaði, mundaðra, munmal, munib, munnuižim, muni, mundandi, ég munda, þeir, þær, þau mundist, mundud, mundaða, munneba, mundaðri, við munduðumst, munnuižid, mundast (þú), munneb, þú mundaðir, þú mundir, munduðum, munmas, mundes, mungoi, ég mundist, munden, munižit, munin, mundist (þið), munižin, munim, þeir, þær, þau mundast, hann, hún, það mundast, munnen, mundaðu, munii, munda (þú), þú mundar, mundið (þið), munnuiži, hann, hún, það mundar, munned, þið munduðuð, mundandist ** ** the mediopassive present participle is extremely rare and normally not used; it is never used attributively or predicatively, only for explicatory subclauses, við mundumst, þú mundist, hann, hún, það mundaðist, mundastu, munduðu, þið munduðust, þú mundast, að mundast, mundaður, mundaðan, munmaspäi, munižid, hann, hún, það mundaði, mundast, mungaha, mundaði, —, munmaha, þeir, þær, þau munduðust, mundasmuniba, munit, þú mundaðist, þeir, þær, þau mundi

Used mostly since Middle Egyptian.
Archaic or greatly restricted in usage by Middle Egyptian. The perfect has mostly taken over the functions of the perfective, and the subjunctive and periphrastic prospective have mostly replaced the prospective.

Only in the masculine.

imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive

past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., gravitèrent/ɡʁa.vi.tɛʁ/, gravita/ɡʁa.vi.ta/, gravite/ɡʁa.vit/, —, gravitait/ɡʁa.vi.tɛ/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., gravitais/ɡʁa.vi.tɛ/, gravitasse/ɡʁa.vi.tas/, gravitaient/ɡʁa.vi.tɛ/, gravitiez/ɡʁa.vi.tje/, gravitez/ɡʁa.vi.te/, graviterai/ɡʁa.vi.tʁe/, graviterez/ɡʁa.vi.tʁe/, graviterons/ɡʁa.vi.tʁɔ̃/, gravitas/ɡʁa.vi.ta/, gravitera/ɡʁa.vi.tʁa/, graviterions/ɡʁa.vi.tə.ʁjɔ̃/, gravitassions/ɡʁa.vi.ta.sjɔ̃/

dum: dumme, dumpronounced with /ð(ʲ)-/, dumma, 1) Only used, optionally, to refer to things whose natural gender is masculine.2) The indefinite superlative forms are only used in the predicative.3) Dated or archaic, dumt, dummeste, dummest2, Note: Some of these forms may be hypothetical. Not everypossible mutated form of every word actually occurs., dummast, 1) When an adjective is applied predicatively to something definite, the corresponding "indefinite" form is used. 2) The "indefinite" superlatives may not be used attributively., dum, dummare, dummaste, ndum, dummere

vis: , (unor) vise, viserne (visine), vísovi, viseve, *vī, Viser, 1) When an adjective is applied predicatively to something definite, the corresponding "indefinite" form is used. 2) The "indefinite" superlatives may not be used attributively., visin, visets, visi, *vīs, visesh, visare, 1) Only used, optionally, to refer to things whose natural gender is masculine.2) The indefinite superlative forms are only used in the predicative.3) Dated or archaic, visest2, visa [visi], vis m, f or n, visom, vise, vī, visa, visovi, visens, vīrēs, Viserna, visane; visene; visa, visa, visi, visen, visele, viser, visurilor, visaste, visen; visa [visi]; viset, visule, vīrium, visane; visene; visa [visi], visast, visovima, Vis f, vīs, visu, viseste, visene2, visere, visove, visar; viser; vis, (unui) vis, viselor, vīribus, (niște) visuri, visului, visit, (unor) visuri, vim, vȋs, visurile, visevet, vist, (un) vis, visova, (niște) vise, viser (visir), viset, visen; visa; viset, vis, vīrēsvīrīs, visul, Visi

piger: pigent/piʒ/, , pigeriez/pi.ʒə.ʁje/, pigrae, pige/piʒ/, pigrī, pigeant/pi.ʒɑ̃/, pigrīs, pigeaient/pi.ʒɛ/, pigeât/pi.ʒa/, pigrōrum, pigez/pi.ʒe/, pigeront/piʒ.ʁɔ̃/, pigeassent/pi.ʒas/, pigeras/piʒ.ʁa/, pigeâtes/pi.ʒat/, pigeas/pi.ʒa/, pigé/pi.ʒe/, pigrārum, pigera/piʒ.ʁa/, pigerons/piʒ.ʁɔ̃/, pigerais/piʒ.ʁɛ/, pigeais/pi.ʒɛ/, piger, pigra, pigerez/piʒ.ʁe/, pigèrent/pi.ʒɛʁ/, pigrum, pigeâmes/pi.ʒam/, pigerait/piʒ.ʁɛ/, pigiez/pi.ʒje/, pigeait/pi.ʒɛ/, pigions/pi.ʒjɔ̃/, pigeasses/pi.ʒas/, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., pigrās, piges/piʒ/, pigerai/piʒ.ʁe/, pigerions/pi.ʒə.ʁjɔ̃/, —, pigeai/pi.ʒe/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., pigrā, pigeons/pi.ʒɔ̃/, pigrō, pigeraient/piʒ.ʁɛ/, pigea/pi.ʒa/, pigeasse/pi.ʒas/, pigeassions/pi.ʒa.sjɔ̃/, pigram, pigrōs, pigeassiez/pi.ʒa.sje/

past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., supas/sy.pa/, —, supèrent/sy.pɛʁ/, supez/sy.pe/, superai/sy.pʁe/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., die supere, supa/sy.pa/, supant/sy.pɑ̃/, supiez/sy.pje/, sie ist super, supâmes/sy.pam/, supes/syp/, supons/sy.pɔ̃/, superiez/sy.pə.ʁje/, supassiez/sy.pa.sje/, superem, superes, die superen, dem superen, (keiner) superen, supé/sy.pe/, superaient/sy.pʁɛ/, der superen, ein superer, der supere

rs: rs, j.rs1, rs, j.rs, rs, rsw5, ḥr rs, rsw, rs, rs.ḫr, r rs, rss, rssj6, rs2, rsw2 5, rsy2 5, j.rs1, j.rsw1 5, rs, rsj6, rsy6, rst, rs.jn, rs, rs, rstj7, Used in Old Egyptian; archaic by Middle Egyptian.
Used mostly since Middle Egyptian.
Archaic or greatly restricted in usage by Middle Egyptian. The perfect has mostly taken over the functions of the perfective, and the subjunctive and periphrastic prospective have mostly replaced the prospective.
Declines using third-person suffix pronouns instead of adjectival endings: masculine .f/.fj, feminine .s/.sj, dual .sn/.snj, plural .sn.
Only in the masculine singular.
Only in the masculine.
Only in the feminine., —, m rs, j.rs1, rs, rsy, rsw5, rstj4, rst4, rs.kꜣ, rs.n

tōgaset, togallaantogallansa, togaasi, togiin, togittasi, togaltamme, togallesi, * Spoken form, usually not written; in writing, the unappended plural form (optionally followed by the full pronoun) is preferred., togami, togaðizk, togaltasi, togaa, togallanne, togaðri, togom, hann, hún, það togast, togallasi, togaltani, togittamme, togillamme, togittani, togiltamme, togastaantogastansa, togillemme, togaðs, atoga, togaamme, togillenne, togattani, þú togaðist, togaðir, togumsk, toguðumsk, að togast, togallamme, togianne, togaða, togastasi, togandist ** ** the mediopassive present participle is extremely rare and normally not used; it is never used attributively or predicatively, only for explicatory subclauses, thoga, togassamme, toga, við toguðum, tōgii, togalta, togattanne, togilleentogillensa, togittanne, togisk, togillesi, togą, fotoga, toga, toginaantoginansa, notoga, togiltani, þú togaðir, togaðu, togir, togillasi, togalle, togiltaantogiltansa, þeir, þær, þau toga, toganne, togistasi, itoga, toguðu, togan, togakseentogaksensa, togaksi, togimsk, togask, togissa, togaðimsk, toge, togientogainrare, togaksenne, tōgaset, ég toga, togiesitogaisirare, togiennetogainnerare, hann, hún, það togar, þeir, þær, þau togi, togana, togassa, togumk, togillanne, togissasi, first-person singular possessor

sin: , gewees, geweest, geween, isín, 2., imu, sīnre, sīne, sino, sīnonō, Genitive, sinina, thī, thik, sī, was, sȋne, sê (sî, sie, sü̂), siu, ni, sin, sinarinnar, ūs, ká, sinlere, dinnen, sinului, sīnne, yi, unk, wäär, ūs, unsik, bist, sinima, dien, sinlerden, em, öm, jüm (en, ēnen, ȫnen), mīn, ís, gī, ge, sîn, sīs, uzen, jû (jûwe, û, jük, gik), sina, sinlerde, sīnin, sinul, sin / sinu, -, sīnra, jou, dîn (dîner), git, sȋn, wes, wis, tet, sīn-, sinar, thīn, sȋna, ninní, mī, me, mik, wāris, ēne, en (ȫne, ȫn), wäärst, sīnarō, kén, né, sīna, sinanna, 3. m, Personal pronouns, (unui) sin, sinove, m gender, kó, iro, sien, 3. n, tét, sȉnovi, wesandi, *art, sinler, hê (hî, hie), it, sinleri, ink, sīnum, sei, seie, sīnun, sinov, sīnu, sinnen, gî (jê, î), waare, sininni, sȋnu, sinden, sienen, minnen, atú, ku, Note: Some of these forms may be hypothetical. sen: , olarda, senilor, sizde, 1) When an adjective is applied predicatively to something definite, the corresponding "indefinite" form is used. 2) The "indefinite" superlatives may not be used attributively., senul, olar, sin, snu, snóm, siz, (unui) sen, sniech, maňa, senaib, sena, senere, snoma, sím, ṡen, senin, bizden, sizden, senule, snům, senden, biziň, senusena†, sně, snu, snoch, snách, seni, onuň, snu, sna, olary, si, snů, sana, senare, senii, (un) sen, ol, meniň, size, seho, sen, bizde, (unor) seni, saňa, senului, olara, unchanged, sent, śú, *modifying a noun whose vocative is different from its nominative

Used mostly since Middle Egyptian.
Archaic or greatly restricted in usage by Middle Egyptian. The perfect has mostly taken over the functions of the perfective, and the subjunctive and periphrastic prospective have mostly replaced the prospective.

aliter: aliterais/a.li.tʁɛ/, alitai/a.li.te/, alitasses/a.li.tas/, alitâmes/a.li.tam/, alitaient/a.li.tɛ/, alité/a.li.te/, aliteriez/a.li.tə.ʁje/, aliter, aliterions/a.li.tə.ʁjɔ̃/, alita/a.li.ta/, alitait/a.li.tɛ/, alitez/a.li.te/, alitent/a.lit/, alitassiez/a.li.ta.sje/, alitassent/a.li.tas/, aliteront/a.li.tʁɔ̃/, aliteraient/a.li.tʁɛ/, alitât/a.li.ta/, alitassions/a.li.ta.sjɔ̃/, alitera/a.li.tʁa/, aliterez/a.li.tʁe/, alite/a.lit/, alitons/a.li.tɔ̃/, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., alitèrent/a.li.tɛʁ/, aliterons/a.li.tʁɔ̃/, —, aliterai/a.li.tʁe/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., alitas/a.li.ta/, alitais/a.li.tɛ/, alitant/a.li.tɑ̃/, aliterait/a.li.tʁɛ/, aliteras/a.li.tʁa/, alitâtes/a.li.tat/, alitasse/a.li.tas/, alitiez/a.li.tje/, alites/a.lit/, alitions/a.li.tjɔ̃/

redire: , redit/ʁə.di/, redesist, redesis, redisiez/ʁə.di.zje/, rièdo, rediroie, redireie, redisoie, rediseie, redïe, redissions/ʁə.di.sjɔ̃/, redisse/ʁə.dis/, en redisant, redis, rediiens, redions, redisiens, redisons, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., redesissons, redesissiens, redisions/ʁə.di.zjɔ̃/, èssere, redira/ʁə.di.ʁa/, rièdono, rediraient/ʁə.di.ʁɛ/, redise/ʁə.diz/, redites, redesissoiz, redesissez, redesissiez, redirai, redirais/ʁə.di.ʁɛ/, Use the gerund of avoir followed by the past participle, redesisses, redisses/ʁə.dis/, rediriez/ʁə.di.ʁje/, rediroient, redireient, rediroit, redireit, redises/ʁə.diz/, redîtes/ʁə.dit/, redìre, rièda, redesimes, redi, redirons/ʁə.di.ʁɔ̃/, redisait/ʁə.di.zɛ/, redesisse, redisant, redites/ʁə.dit/, redisoit, rediseit, redire, redît/ʁə.di/, redisant/ʁə.di.zɑ̃/, redïent, redimes, redions, redisons, rediront/ʁə.di.ʁɔ̃/, redisiiens, redisiens, redis/ʁə.di/, rediras, redirait/ʁə.di.ʁɛ/, redist, redisent/ʁə.diz/, redisaient/ʁə.di.zɛ/, redit, redirent/ʁə.diʁ/, redesistes, riède, rediront, avoir redit, redìto, redisons/ʁə.di.zɔ̃/, rediroiz, redireiz, redirez, redirez/ʁə.di.ʁe/, redisiiez, redisiez, redient, redîmes/ʁə.dim/, rediriiez, rediriez, rediras/ʁə.di.ʁa/, redisoies, rediseies, rediroies, redireies, rediriiens, rediriens, redesissent, rièdano, redisoient, rediseient, redistrent, rediiez, redisiez, redïes, redirions/ʁə.di.ʁjɔ̃/, redissiez/ʁə.di.sje/, redirons, —, rièdi, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., redisais/ʁə.di.zɛ/, redira, redissent/ʁə.dis/, redirai/ʁə.di.ʁe/

malalarının

malalarının, (unor) malale, mólum, möluð, malasta, malasında or malalarında, maloillesi, mǿlir, þeir, þær, þau mala, * Spoken form, usually not written; in writing, the unappended plural form (optionally followed by the full pronoun) is preferred., maloiltamme, malalar, mólu, leis an mala
don mhala, malayı, malasını, malattasi, malasını or malalarını, Nominative (first), malalleni, maloiltani, hann, hún, það malaði, Vocative, maloihini, malisk, mōl, malaksemme, malts, þú malaðist, malaðra, malasının or malalarının, malanızdan, maloissaanmaloissansa, malandist ** ** the mediopassive present participle is extremely rare and normally not used; it is never used attributively or predicatively, only for explicatory subclauses, maloihimme, malamıza, malalarınız, maloiltasi, malanızın, að malast, þú malir, malaðrar, malim, malojennemalainnerare, malast (þú), maloihin, móluð, malaa, Dative (fourth), hann, hún, það malar, þú malaðir, malin, mōlus, mōlos, malandan, malalarınızın, malalle, malamme, malums, -oms, malatta, malaksesi, malalarımızda, malanasi, mǿlið, an mhala, malalarınıza, mólzk, malām, malamızda, malalarım, maloissasi, malallaanmalallansa, malanızı, við mölum, malalarına, mǫlumk, malasında, maloistaanmaloistansa, māla, vīr, malanani, við möluðumst, malamızın, malen, mald, malde, mōlis, mōles, malið, malasi, malalarıma, maliði *, malallesi, mali, male, maloinesi, maloistamme, malassasi, melsk, að mala, —, malanın, maloineni, mōlin, malattaanmalattansa, malaltani, þū, mals, malāni, maloiksemme, malalarını, þið möluðuð, Genitive, mōlins, mali, maloinemme, malojen, malamda, maloilleni, maloilta, malalelor, malasına or malalarına, þú malist, malums, maloms, a mhala, malalarımda, malamız, við mölumst, malaðan, mālīs, maloillenne, malað, Ablative (fifth), maloillanne, mālārum, þú malast, þú malar, maloinasi, þeir, þær, þau möluðust, ég malist, malanne, þēr, malaansa, malastamme, maloittanne, maloiksenne, malu, malakseenmalaksensa, þeir, þær, þau malist, maloiltaanmaloiltansa, mólsk, Bare forms

velim: bȕdēmo velili2, bíli su velili2, velite, bȉo bih velio2, velili su2, vele, velio sam2, bíli ste velili2, velim / velju, velio je2, bíli bismo velili2, velili bi2, veljaste, bȉo si velio2, bȕdēš velio2, veli, velimo, veljasmo, velili ste2, 1   Croatian spelling: others omit the infinitive suffix completely and bind the clitic.2   For masculine nouns; a feminine or neuter agent would use the feminine and neuter gender forms of the active past participle and auxiliary verb, respectively.3   Often replaced by the past perfect in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
4   Often replaced by the conditional I in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.

leis na coin, Note: Some of these forms may be hypothetical. Not every possible mutated form of every word actually occurs., a choin, leis na cúnna, conaib, cúcoin (archaic, dialectal), an chú, na coin, Initial mutations of a following adjective:

past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., disiez/di.zje/, dîmes/dim/, non diciàmo, dicènte, dirài, dìssero, desissons, desissiens, dist, dirait/di.ʁɛ/, dicémmo, direz/di.ʁe/, dirò, desisses, diront/di.ʁɔ̃/, disais/di.zɛ/, disse/dis/, dis/di/, diriiez, diriez, dicéste, diréte, disent/diz/, non dìte, dicéssi, non dìcano, diroiz, direiz, direz, diciàte, Use the gerund of avoir followed by the past participle, distrent, dise/diz/, dites/dit/, en disant, diront, disait/di.zɛ/, diras/di.ʁa/, dicevàte, desissent, dìssi, dira/di.ʁa/, diiens, dions, disiens, disons, dissent/dis/, dì', dì1,2, dira, diiez, disiez, dicévano, dites, dîtes/dit/, dïe, dicévi, dìsse, desimes, disoit, diseit, avoir dit, dient, desistes, dìte, dìcono, dimes, dions, disons, dirai/di.ʁe/, dit, disiiez, disiez, desist, dìco, diciàmo, dis, diroies, direies, diroie, direie, avére, dìce, desissoiz, desissez, desissiez, dirànno, dirons, détto, dirémmo, dissions/di.sjɔ̃/, dirèi, dìre, non dìca, desisse, dît/di/, dicéva, dicésse, dicésti, dirèbbero, dirébbero, diréste, disiiens, disiens, diriez/di.ʁje/, dirèbbe, dirébbe, dïes, dirions/di.ʁjɔ̃/, dissiez/di.sje/, dicévo, diras, dirà, dises/diz/, disoie, diseie, dire, dìci, dirai, —, disant/di.zɑ̃/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., disons/di.zɔ̃/, dirésti, desis, diroient, direient, disant, dirais/di.ʁɛ/, dirent/diʁ/, dïent

mariti: bȕdēmo marili2, marim, marit će1mariće, bȉo si mario2, marili smo2, mario bi2, bíli bismo marili2, bȕdēš mario2, mare, marili biste2, bíli smo marili2, marasmo, bíli biste marili2, bȕdēm mario2, bȕdēte marili2, mari, marah, bȉo bi mario2, Future I, marili su2, marili m / marile f / marila n, 1   Croatian spelling: others omit the infinitive suffix completely and bind the clitic.2   For masculine nouns; a feminine or neuter agent would use the feminine and neuter gender forms of the active past participle and auxiliary verb, respectively.3   Often replaced by the past perfect in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
4   Often replaced by the conditional I in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
  * Note: The aorist and imperfect have nowadays fallen into disuse in many dialects and therefore they are routinely replaced by the past perfect in both formal and colloquial speech., marahu, maraste, marili bismo2, maraše, mario si2, bȉo je mario2, mario je2, marit ćete1marićete, bíli ste marili2, mario bih2, mario sam2, marit ćeš1marićeš, mariš, mario m / marila f / marilo n, bíli bi marili2, bíli su marili2, bȉo bih mario2, bȕdū marili2, bȉo sam mario2, marit ćemo1marićemo, —, marimo, marite, marili ste2, Imperfect, marili bi2, bȕdē mario2, marit ću1mariću

past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., celerent, celeru, celez, celeroient, celeroyent, celai, celames, celasse/sə.las/, celé, celerem, cèleras/sɛl.ʁa/, celeroit, celeroyt, celeras, celere, en celant, celerům, celassions/sə.la.sjɔ̃/, celerů, celas, celasses/sə.las/, celeriez, celeryez, celions, celyons, celaient/sə.lɛ/, Use the gerund of avoir followed by the past participle, celassent/sə.las/, celoies, celeies, celoes, celeves, celeris, celerima, celiez/sə.lje/, celions/sə.ljɔ̃/, celery, 2 The gerund was held to be invariable by grammarians of the early 17th century, and was usable with preposition en, as in Modern French, although the preposition was not mandatory (Anne Sancier-Château [1995], op. cit., p. 180)., celeriiez, celeriez, celeroies, celereies, cela, celer, cèle/sɛl/, celent, celerium, celeront, celiiens, celiens, celeroiz, celereiz, celerez, celassiez/sə.la.sje/, celeribus, çouz, cèles/sɛl/, celant/sə.lɑ̃/, cèlent/sɛl/, celissons, celissiens, celast, celerons, celoit, celeit, celot, celeve, celerai, celeray, celât/sə.la/, celeria, 1 The present participle was variable in gender and number until the 17th century (Anne Sancier-Château [1995], Une esthétique nouvelle: Honoré d'Urfé, correcteur de l'Astrée, p. 179). latent: latent, ein latenter, eine latente, einem latenten, latenta, die latente, einer latenten, latenților, 1) When an adjective is applied predicatively to something definite, the corresponding "indefinite" form is used. 2) The "indefinite" superlatives may not be used attributively., latente, der latenten, —2, den latenten, die latenten, 1) Only used, optionally, to refer to things whose natural gender is masculine.2) The indefinite superlative forms are only used in the predicative.3) Dated or archaic, eines latenten, latenten, latenter, latentes, der latente, (keine) latenten, des latenten, dem latenten, latenții, sie sind latent, ein latentes, latentelor, latentele, latentului, das latente, er ist latent, latenți, sie ist latent, latentă, latentul, —, (keiner) latenten, es ist latent, latentem, einen latenten, latentei, (keinen) latenten

mn: mn.n, mn, mntj7, r mn, mnn, mnnj6, mn2, mnw2 5, mny2 5, mntj4, mnt4, mnw, mn.ḫr, mn.jn, mnn, m mn, Used in Old Egyptian; archaic by Middle Egyptian.
Used mostly since Middle Egyptian.
Archaic or greatly restricted in usage by Middle Egyptian. The perfect has mostly taken over the functions of the perfective, and the subjunctive and periphrastic prospective have mostly replaced the prospective.
Declines using third-person suffix pronouns instead of adjectival endings: masculine .f/.fj, feminine .s/.sj, dual .sn/.snj, plural .sn.
Only in the masculine singular.
Only in the masculine.
